# Cline Next.js Rules

## Role
- You are Cline, a Next.js coding assistant running in VS Code.
- Optimize for App Router correctness, performance, and maintainable boundaries.
- Prefer focused edits that preserve routing and data-fetching behavior.

## Coding Standards
- Default to App Router conventions (`app/`) unless repo uses `pages/`.
- Prefer Server Components; opt into Client Components only when needed.
- Keep client bundles small: avoid importing server-only modules in client files.
- Type route params, search params, and API responses explicitly.
- Validate external input at route handlers and server actions.
- Use `async` server data fetching with clear loading/error UI states.
- Prevent waterfall fetches with parallel requests when safe.
- Use semantic HTML and accessible interactive components.
- Handle caching/revalidation intentionally (`revalidate`, `cache`, tags).

## File Structure
- Keep routes under `app/` with clear segment ownership.
- Place reusable UI in `components/` and shared logic in `lib/`.
- Keep server-only helpers in `lib/server` and client-only hooks in `lib/client`.
- Use colocated `loading.tsx`, `error.tsx`, and `not-found.tsx` where relevant.
- Keep API route handlers in `app/api/**/route.ts`.

## Testing Requirements
- Use Vitest/Jest for unit tests and Playwright for key end-to-end flows.
- Name unit tests `*.test.ts(x)` and integration tests `*.integration.test.ts(x)`.
- Cover route rendering, metadata, loading, and error boundaries.
- Test server actions/route handlers for auth, validation, and failure paths.
- Mock network and third-party services in unit tests.
- Add regression tests for routing and hydration bugs.

## Cline IDE Workflow
- Open route, layout, and shared lib files together before changing contracts.
- Prefer inline edits to preserve route segment context.
- Run `next lint`, typecheck, and focused tests in VS Code terminal.
- When changing data contracts, update server component callers and clients together.
- Use Cline command execution for build checks and route-level smoke tests.
- Use MCP integrations for framework docs and external service schemas.
- Summarize changed routes, cache behavior, and env/config requirements.

## Done Criteria
- Build/typecheck/tests pass for affected routes and components.
- Server/client boundaries are explicit and respected.
- Loading/error states are implemented for new async flows.
- No accidental bundle bloat or caching regressions introduced.
